==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*baidia-'', from Indo-European ''*bheidh-'' ‘persuade, agree’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[bedian|bēdian]], Old Norse [[beiða]], Gothic [[𐌱𐌰𐌹𐌳𐌾𐌰𐌽]]

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[πείθω]], Latin [[fidere]], Slavic ''*-bīdītī'' (Old Church Slavonic [[бѣждѫ]], Russian [[бедить]]), Albanian [[bint]]

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'bæ:dan/

===Verb===
{{Unicode|'''bǣdan'''}} (class 1 weak)
# to [[constrain]], to [[incite]], to [[compel]]
#:''Ðæs his lufu bædeþ'': whom his love constrains.  (''Exeter Book'')

